He tells us himself that he was acquainted wit-h Augustus, and Tacitus describes this acquaintance as friendship, adding that it remained unim- paired by the historiau's praises of Pompey. As all the anec- dotes and criticisms quoted from Livy by Seneca and Quin- tilian are connected with rhetoric, it is not unlikely that he followed the profession of a rhetorician in Rome. We are perhaps not justified in placing Claudius, who afterwards be- came emperor, among the list of his pupils, but it was by his advice that that unfortunate grandson of Livia devoted himself to historica] writing. Livy died at Padua in the year 17 A.D.

Livy's works on philosophy, and his dialogues, which are described by Seneca as 'partly philosophical and partly histor- ical, are entirely lost3 and of his great work, originally consist- ing of 150 books, extending to the death of Drusus, Ro. 9, there only, remain thirty-five books and a few inconsiderable fragments. These books are: the first decade, containing his account of what happened from the founding of the city down to the year 293 B.C.; the third and-fourth decades (embracing
